{"/service/ndnp/me/batch_me_burdin_ver03/data/sn82014248/0051368244A/1908010201/0024.xml":{"full_text":"Daily Kennebec Journal\nE8TABLI8HED 182>\nM* notice whatever will ba takaa af\nunsigned communication*.\nThe Journal cannot be held responsible\nfor tbe preservation or return of re*\nJected communications.\nAddress all communications relating to\nsubscriptions and advertisements to\nBURLEIGH FLYNT, Publisher*\nAugusta* Maine.\nThursday( January 2, 1908.\nEverything seems to be ready for\nthe annual ice harvest on the Kenne\nbec except the ice.\nWell, what if you did crack one or\ntwo of those resolutions yesterday?\nPatch them up and start in over again\ntoday.\nA New Yorker aged 86 has just\neloped with a young woman over half\nft. century his junior, and this is a\nreminder that nothing has been heard\nof late about the contemplated\nmatrimonial venture of Uncle Gassa\nway Davis.\nA dispatch from Texas says that\nWilliam J. llryan is on a hunting trip\nin that state and that he shot 25 ducks\non one day recently. But, alas, dis\npatches of this kind do not mean what\nt hey 4used to. It will henceforth be\nnecessary to add \u2018\u2018of Florida\u201d or \u201cof\nNebraska\u201d when William J. Bryan's\nname appears In the newspapers.\n\"One hundred brand-new $10 gold\npieces! Can you imagine a prettier\nsight?\" asks the Atlanta Georgian.\nBure! One hundred brand-new $20\ngold pieces.\u2014Washington Post.\nThat Post paragraph*-!- is always\noriginal. The query of the Georgia\npaper has been going tin- rounds for\nsome time and in every other instance\nthe answer has been \"Two hundred\nbrand-new $10 gold pieces.\u201d\nIt can no longer be charged that\nAmerica is too sordid to have a proper\nappreciation of fine literature and\nliterary genius. An Indiana novelist\nwho disturbed the peace of his city in\ntlie early morning hours by cutting up\nhigh Jinks, resisting an officer and\nprecipitating a riot was exalted above\ntlie vulgar herd by the police court\nJudge, and instead of being sent up for\n.10 days the consideration of his case\nwas indefinitely postponed.\nThe announcement that the Maine\nSportsman's l'ish and Game Associa\ntion at its next meeting at Bangor will\ndiscuss the advisability of a hunting\nlicense for residents of this State is a\nreminder that exactly this kind of a\nlicense has just been recommended by\nthe fish ami game commissioners of\nthe state of New York. And when a\nNew Yorker buys a license for hunting\ngame within the confines of his own\nstate he stands a relatively small\nshow of getting anything for liis\nmoney.\nThe outside newspapers are dis\ncussing with no small degree of\nsurprise and with the warmest kind\nof praise the report of the Maine\nStale prison which shows that the\ninstitution is practically self-support\ning. The condition of things at\nThomaston in this respect differs very\ngreatly from that prevailing at the\npenal institutions in our sister states,\nand they And it hard to understand\nhow Maine manages it. It is a very\nhigh tribute to the system in operation\nat our State prison and to the sound\nbusiness methods of those now in\ncharge of the institution.\nWith hardly more than a line of\nobituary in the newspapers the old\nSaratoga, once the pride of the Ameri\ncan navy, has passed Into the hands\nof Boston junk dealers. This famous\nold ship, which was one of the largest\nand most imposing of its type when\nbuilt, was a product of the navy yard\nat Kittery. it was sent to the African\ncoast in 1812 to assist in stopping slave\ntrade ami it played a prominent part in\nthe eontliet with the pirates of the\nEarbary States. It saw service in\nboth the Mexican and the Civil wars\nIts greatest honor, however, was its\nshare in the mission of peace to Japan\nIn 1S51, when Commodore Perry opened\nto civilization the empire which is now\ntaking its place as one of the great\npowers of the world. And now the old\nSaratoga Is being broken tip for junk\nand its passing is almost unnoticed.\nThe price of silver has had a great\ndrop of late, and although it was\nT.\u2019orth as much as 71 cents a year ago\nit now sells for only '.3 cents, which is\none of its lowest prices in recent years.\nOne reason for the great drop is the\nsimple fact that China and India have\nstopped buying it. and as this country\nfloes not need all the silver which its\nmines produce there is bound to be a\ndepreciation when our best customers\nturn away. Although silver is still\nclassed as a \u201cprecious\u201d metal, its price\nfluctuates much more violently than\nmost of the things which are never\ngiven this classification. In striking\ncontrast is the cost of steel rails, foi\nwhile the white metal which is usee\nfor money has lost one-fourth of it;\nvalue h\\ a single year, the enormou:\ntransportation business of the counter\nIs carried over rails whose price ha:\nremained at J2S per ton for the pas\nIt dozen years. __\nThe Famous Dead of 1907.\nEach year has its long list of\nfamous dead, but the list for 1907\nseems shorter than usual. Two rulers\nof foreign countries are on the list.\nKing Oscar of Sweden and the Shah\nof Persia. Of the writers who died\nduring the year, Dr. John Watson,\nMoncure D. Conway and Thomas\nEailey Aldrich are among the fore\nmost. Augustus St. Gaudens was the\none great artist to die last year, but\namong the scientists are numbered\nLord Kelvin, Professor Asaph Hall,\nMaurice Loewy, director of the Paris\nobservatory; Alexander Stewart\nHerschel, another astronomer of note;\nProfessor Angelo Heilprin, the\ngeologist, and Professor Mendeleef,\nthe celebrated chemist. Among\nstatesmen and politicians of promi\nnence in the United States were Gen\neral Russell A. Alger, former Gover\nnor Frank W. Higgins of New York,\nGalusha A. Grow; Daniel H. Chamber\nlain, the noted reconstructionist Gov\nernor of South Carolina; Edwin H.\nConger, United States minister to\nPekin during the Boxer rebellion;\nUnited States Senators John T. Mor\ngan of Alabama and Edmund W. P^t\ntus of the same state, and Senator\nMallory of Florida.\nThe Embezzlements of 1907.\nAccording to the Chicago Tribune,\nwhich collects interesting statistics of\nall kinds with great care and thorough\nness, there was less dishonesty in\n1907 among the bank men of the coun- j\ntry than in 1906. Whether men have\nbeen more closely watched or have\nfound it easier to resist temptation, the\nfact remains that the embezzlements,\nforgeries, bank wreckings, etc., for 1907\napproximate $11,000,000, while in 1906\nthey footed-up $14,739,000, the largest\ntotal since 1891, when they aggregated\nThe country has grown\nenormously in wealth during the last 13\nyears. There are more banks and more\npe .pie handling trust funds. There\nwas a financial panic last year, and\nsuch a panic is likely to expose what\never embezzlers or bank wreckers there\nmay be. Perhaps the wonder is that\nonly $11,000,000 has gone astray.\nOf tiiat sum the banks and trust com\npanies lost $.',.000,000, mostly through\ndishonest officials or employees. Public\nofficials handling city, county, state, or\nnational funds have been more success\nful in keeping their hands from pick\ning and stealing last year than they\nwere in 1906. Their peculations aggre\ngated only $778,000, while In 1906 they\namounted to about $1,700,000. More\nmoney was handled and less was stolen.\nThere has been gratifying grogress in\none particular at least.\nJames Dumps, Democratic Editor.\nDo you know Mr. James Dumps?\nYou ought to. He is the doubting\nbrother in every community who wears\ngreen glasses and talks \"a blue\nstreak.\u201d\nIf things are bad he says they are\nworse. If affairs are on the mend he is\nsure there will be another break. When\nthings begin to boom he is confident\nthat it is only a spurt, that prosperity\ncan't last.\nAs a matter of fact Mr. Dumps is\nwrong about ninety-nine times in a\nhundred. I\u2019.emember that when you\nhear him croaking. The safest thing\nto do is to laugh at him. and don't for\nget that confidence begets confidence.\nOur country lias safely weathered\nthe little storm that made you cling to\nyour money, and the best men in the\nland\u2014the men who are doing the work\nare certain that good times are\nheaded this way and coming with a\nrush.\nHear th< r.r\u2014they know what they are\ntalking about\u2014and don't listen to or\ndon't he a \"Dumps.\u201d\u2014Xew York Tele\ngram\nThose sensible remarks are respect\nfully recommended to the consideration\nof those who ha%\u2019e been reading the\nlugubrious and lacrymose wails of the\nWaterville Sentinel and other organs\nof the calamity Democracy. To be\ntrue to his calling a Democratic editor\nlias to lie n professional pessimist and\na chronic kicker, wear blue glasses and\nsuffer each day an attack of acute\ndyspepsia. He is just the James\nDumps whom our Xew York con\ntemporary has in mind.\nSince Prof. Burns of Detroit. Mich.,\nso unceremoniously put an end to the\nchampionship aspirations of Prof.\nMoir of England, the English sporting\nwriters are taking the view that\npugilism is a disgusting sport any\nway and unworthy of Englishmen.\nThey have even discovered that Moir\nis a Scotchman and not the typical\nEnglishman which they represented\nhim as being before his downfall.\nEngland was once the nursery' of \"the\nnoble art of self defense,\u201d but it has\nbeen unable to produce a heavyweight\nchampion in our day and generation,\nand the only hope of the English\npugilists is to follow the lead of the\nHenley regatta committee and bar\nforeigners from competition.\nWilliam James Bryan, the new Sena\ntor from Florida, is just one year older\nthan the law requires to make a man\neligible to a seat in the United States\nSenate. He is tall and of athletic\nbuild, with a frank smile and of the\ntype which has made the drawings of\nHoward Chandler Christy famous. He\nis a fine lawyer, a splendid speaker,\nand a hard worker.\nH:nry Hadley of Xew York, who is\nin Berlin, directed the Philharmonic\nOrchestra of that city on Friday eve\nning. and was cordially received. The\n1 orchestra played his new symphony\nwhich will be given in America for tire\nfirst time in January by the Bostor\nSymphony Orchestra. Mr. Hadlej\nwill direct the opera at Mainz this win'\n\n_\nLast Night.\nLast night I heard you singing, and th\u00ab\nsong\nCalled back the olden years.\nAnd di earns and hopes that had beer\nburied long\nAwoke to life again the gentle tears,\nThe pain and heartache, all the doubt!\nand fears,\nThat long had vexed me, with the straii\ntook flight.\nAnd I was back within golden years.\nLast night-last night!\nLast night I hoard you singing and th<\nsong\nV. as cne vou sang to me.\nIn those old days before the doubt and\nwrong\nHad pierced my soul with their in\ntensity.\nThe shadows that had hovered long did\nflee\nAmi all the world was filled with jo>\nand light:\nHope sane again her siren song to me,\nLast night-last night!\nViola Virginia Antl'-y.\nLots of interesting reading in the\nmany State department reports now\nbeing made public.\nThe Maine State Press Association\nwill meet in Portland Jan. 23 and 24. It\nwill be the 4.\">th annual meeting.\nEdward Payson Weston will be in\nMaine on a lecturing tour later in the\nwinter. He will not make the trip afoot,\nhowever, this time.\nAsa Riggs of Belfast is probably the\noldest baker in active business in the\nState, as he has been in the bakery\nbusiness over 60 years. Mr. Riggs will\nbe SI years old the fifth day of Janu\nary, and goes to his bakery daily, still\ndoing some of the cooking himself.\nThe official list of vessels built in\nthe District of Bath for the year of\n1007 shows nineteen vessels, viz., four\nschooners, one steamer, one yacht,\neight scows, and five barges with a\ntotal gross tonnage of 13,584.24 tons.\nThe souevnir hunters are making it\nlikely that when Wiscasset\u2019s famous\nold Paul Revere bell is recast it will\nweigh less than before it was broken\nin. pieces by its fall from the steeple\nof the burning church in December.\nThe boll was purchased in 1800\nand is one of the three original bells\nof this make owned in New England.\nThe other two are owned in Bingham\nand Portsmouth, N. H. The W iscas\nset bell was removed from the old\nchurch in 1840 and placed on the\nnew church dedicated that year. Dur\ning the recent fire the bell was broken\nwhen it fell to the ground and was\nscattered about in the ruins. The so\nciety intend to have it recast and al\nthough it will be impossible to gather\nthe whole of the metal it is expected\nenough will be recovered to make a\ngood sized bell. The bell weighed\n900 pounds and up to the present\nt\u2019,me all but 200 pounds have been\nrecovered. Many people have secured\nsmall pieces as souvenirs so that the\nnew bell will not be as heavy as the\noriginal.\nHere is a belated Christmas story\nfrom Bar Harbor. At one of the\nchurch Christmas trees, the success of\nthe entire affair came near being dis\narranged through the trust tactics of\none small girl, who showed talents\nthat ought surely to brand her as a\ncaptain of industry\u2014or the peniten\ntiary. The dignified Santa Claus\nwould call off the names of the re\ncipients ot the presents, and a number\nof times when the child in o.uestion\nwas not in the hall, a small girl vol\nunteered the information that she lived\nnear them. The last bag of candy on\nthe tree was taken off. and the small\ngirl departed with an armful of pack\nages on her mission of errand girl.\nA day or two later complaints began\nto come in from tearful youngsters wlto\nhad not received their presents. So\nmanv and so emphatic were the com\nplaints. accompanied by sobs and boo\nhoos of various sizes and dimensions\nthat tile Santa Claus pro tern, decided\nto investigate, and to call in the ser\nvices of an officer. On reaching the\nlittle girl's home on the outskirts of\nthe town, ami suddenly entering. a\nveritable mine of presents was found.\nThere were bags of candy, dolls, hand\nkerchiefs, neckties, shaving mugs, and\na thousand and one tilings that the\naverage doting relative will persist in\ngiving as Christmas remembrances.\nShe had decided that home was the\nbest place, and that there was too\nmuch labor involved in distributing the\nvarious presents. The small girl is\nnow taking her meals off the mantel\npiece, and a big policeman was made\nan involuntary Santa Claus.\nCaptain Frank Patten of the five\nmasted schooner Kineo is at his hopie\nin Bath for a brief visit. He arrived\nin Boston Saturday from Newport\nNews with a cargo of \"105 tons of coal.\nThree years ago the vessel made her\nla.it trip to Boston. From there she\nwent to Norfolk and, for the govern\nment, loaded a cargo of coal which she\ndelivered at Cavite. From the Philip\npines she went to Australia and load\ned coal for Hawaii. Then she took\non 3100 tons of sugar at Kahului and\nsailed for Philadelphia. That passage\nwas tlte most eventful in the vessel's\ncareer, and hardly a man on board\never expected to make another port\nCaught oiT Cape Horn in a series ol\nfearful hurricanes, the schooner tva<\npartially dismantled. Repairs wer<\neffected, but another storm undid the\nwork. Five times the schooner was\ncrippled by the carrying away o\nparts of her gear. She was driven of\nher course thousands of miles. Ai\ntime passed and nothing was hearr\nfrom the vessel the owners and friend\nof the captain and crew became\nalarmed. When she was out 150 day\nall hope was abandoned and it wa\nbelieved she had foundered in one o\nthe severe storms encountered off th\nSouth American coast. Captain Pat\nten was accompanied by his wife an\nlittle daughter. Just 210 days fror\nthe time the vessel sailed from Kahulc\nshe reached Delaware Breakwatei\nHer supply of provisions was nearl\nexhausted and those on hoard had suf\nfered considerably. Capt. Patten'\nlittle daughter was the heroine of th\npassage. She cheered the men whe\nthey were utterly discouraged and i\nthe worst storms she displayed Spat\ntan bravery.\n1 MAINE EDITORIAL COMMENT.\nLeap Year Philosophy.\n(Portland Express.)\nThis talk abcut the timid bachelor\nand leap year does well enough for par\nugrapher, but there\u2019s nothing in it. The\ntimid bachelor is in no danger. He who\nhasn\u2019t the nerve to propose to a win\nsome girl himself will never find said\nwinsome girl putting herself to the\ntrouble to propose to him. The men\n1 who are worth having are the ones who\ncapture their prizes for themselves, not\nthose who sit back and wait to be\ncaught.\nDeer Not Decreasing.\n(Biddeford Journal.)\nAccording to Maine W oods, puolished\nat Phillips, there is no truth in the con\ntention that the deer of the state are\ndecreasing in numbers. On the con\ntrary it is said that when the real fig\nures of the past season\u2019s killings are\nconsidered the year 1907 compares fav\norably with average seasons. Com\nplete returns from the railroads of\nshipments of game are quoted to bear\nlout this assertion. The total recorded\nshipments of game over all railroads in\n.Maine show that 1907 was just 436 deer\nahead of the similar figures of 1906, and\ntiiat despite the fact that there are re\ncorded some 300 less out of the state\nhunters\u2019 licenses and a very poor sea\nson on account of the absence of snow,\nwhich was missing during the vital part\nj of the season when hunters are attract\ned to Maine to hunt moose and deer by\ntracking them in the snow, and even,\ntoday, the woods are void of it. a most\nwonderful open season. It is true that\nthe decrease in the number of licenses\nwas- partly due to the financial panic,\nfor Maine\u2019s sportsmen draw from the\nranks of men in financial and commer\ncial business. With a loss of 200 or\nmore big game hunters and a poor sea\nson. the final official record of game\nshipments from Maine is eminently\nsatisfactory.\n\nWell Behaved Sagadahoc.\n(Bath Independent.)\nThat Sagadahoc is a remarkably or\nderly county we have always main\ntained and the fact that the grand jury\nonly found one indictment at the pres\nent term of court is convincing evi\ndence of that fact. Bath and Sagada\nhoc are law abiding and made up of as\ngood a class of people as can be found\nin the country.\nNew State Laws.\n(Portland Press.)\nSeveral important acts of the Leg\nislature go into effect today. These\ninclude the State roads act, the act in\nregard to school apropriations, the\npure drugs and medicines act, and the\nact relating to bait barrels. Of these\nthe most important is the law to pro\nvide for State aid and for the ex\npenditure of other public moneys in\nthe permanent improvement of mam\nhighways, since it marks some radical\nchanges in policy. The objects as\nstated are \"to obtain a more uniform\nsystem for the permanent improve\nment of main highways throughout\nthe State, to secure the co-operation\nof the municipalities and the State in\nproviding means therefor, and to pro\nvide for more economical and efficient\nexpenditure of moneys appropriated\nfor highway construction and repair.\u201d\nThese are highly desirable purposes,\nand if tlve law succeeds in accomplish\ning what its framers hoped for it will\nconfer great public benefit. Very\nlikely there are states with worse\nroads, but Maine needs better ones\nvery much.\nThe law as it now stands seems to\nestablish a fairly consistent and sys\ntematic policy. In the first place,\nthere is a State highway department,\nwith a commissioner at the head, em\npowered to appoint a civil engineer as\nassistant. To provide funds a State\ntax is assessed of one-third of a mill\non each dollar of valuation, and each\ntown is required to set apart out of\nthe money annually appropriated for\nthe repair of highways specified\namounts l'or the permanent improve\nment of its main highways under the\nadvice of the State commissioner,\nthese amounts to run from fifty cents\non each thousand dollars of valuation\nin towns having less than $200,000 of\nvaluation, down to 8 1-3 cents on the\nthousand for towns with valuation of\n$15,000,000 and upwards. That is to\nsay, a town with $200,000 valuation\nwould have to set apart $100 for per\nmanent improvement, and Portland\nwould have to provide in the same\nway something over $4000. In case of\nunincorporated townships having\nhighways the county commissioners\nare required to set aside in the same\nway 33 1-3 cents on each thousand of\nvaluation. Hitherto the raising of\nmoney for State roads in consideration\nof receiving State aid has been volun\ntary with the towns, but now it be\ncomes compulsory. The towns have\nto set apart their quotas, and if th\u00bby\nwish State aid they must set apart 50\nper cent additional, taking a vote each\nyear on the question of State aid. To\nthose applying for State aid and com\nplying with the conditions amounts\nare to be apportioned varying from\n75 cents on each dollar set apart by\nthe town of one million valuation and\nupwards to two dollars for each dollar\nset apart by the town of $100,000\nvaluation or less. The work is to be\ndone under the supervision of the\nState commissioner. To illustrate, a\ntown of $100,000 valuation would have\nto set apart in the first place a State\nroad fund of $50. It would then have\nto add 50 per cent, or $25, in order to\nsecure State aid. The State would\nthen give two dollars for one, or $150,\nand the town would have for the pur\npose all told $225. Suppose the city\nto have set apart $6000, it would re\nceive $4500 from the State. It will be\nseen that the act as thus outlined is\na radical departure from the former\nState road policy. It ought to give\nI road building a decided boom.\nThe new school law reduces the\namount which towns are required to\nI raise for the support of common\nschools from 80 cents per inhabitant\nto 55 cents and raises the State tax\nfor the same purpose from one mill to\none and one-half mills on the total\nf valuation of the State. This relieve?\n5 the small towns by so much and\nthrows the burden more onto the gon\nj eral property of the State; so that\n1 while some of these towns are com\ni plaining of the State roads act as un\nfair to them, since they have no use\nfor such roads and do not see wh>\nthey should be required to appropriate\ns fifty cents on the thousand for them\ne the school act provides ample com\npensation.\nr. The pure food and drug law make;\nit unlawful to sell, transport, offer fot\nsale or transportation, or to manufac\nA\nlure any adulterated or misbranded\narticle of food or drug. The defini\ntions of what is considered by the law\nas adulteration or misbranding are\ngiven at length and with such\nparticularity that there need be no\nmistake, and the penalty is $100 fine\nfor the first offence and $200 for each\nsubsequent offence. The new law\nregulating the size of clam bait bar\nrels is chiefly of interest to fishermen.\nVOICES OF THE PRESS.\nOur Foreign Relations.\n(Philadelphia Inquirer.)\n\u201cNo Englishman. I hope,\u201d says Am\nbassador Bryce, \u201cconsiders himself in\nthe United States a foreigner.\u201d Cer\ntainly not. He is usually a son-in-law\nor a brother-in-law, or has ambitions\nin that direction.\nThe Test of the Fleet.\n(Atlanta Constitution.)\nNever before has the integrity of\nbolt and rivet and keel, the stoutness\nand staving powers of tho engines and\nthe seamanship of officers and men of\nthe ileet that is the nation's naval bul\nwark been subjected to such u critical\ntest. We have no accurate, actual\nknowledge of what we may expect\nfrom the weakness or the strength of\nthese armor-clad monsters. It is right,\nit is necessary, it is patriotic, that we\nshould have this knowledge; and that\nwe should be assured, as we will be\nassured, that America relies on no tin-\nknown quantity when she pins hereon-\nfidence and taith to these defenders of I\nher safety and reputation.\nSocial Life in College.\n(Minneapolis Journal.)\nThere is, and has been for some time,\na suspicion that social observances\nwere becoming too strenuous in the\ncolleges of America. The expense of\nattending college has increased and is\nincreasing, and while a portion of this\nis attributable to the rise in the cost\not living, the fact remains that social\nlife is accountable for a great deal\nmore of it. The law and public opin\nion will doubtless sustain the faculty\nof any college in making such Just re\nstrictions upon the social life of the\nstudent as will emphasize the main ob\nject of atendanoe upon college, that is.\nthe mastering of the course of study.\nThis is in the interest of the student\nhimself, and it is a course for which\nhe will deeply thank the faculty\u2014\nlater on.\nDavis\u2019 Speech Dissected.\n(Chicago Evening Post.)\nUpon careful analysis of the maiden\nspeech of Senator Jeff Davis of Ar\nkansas we find the main ingredients\nto be;\nThree vainglorious bits of self\npraise.\nFour mixed metaphors applied to\nthe trusts.\nSix Lromidic similes for money.\nOr.e inaccurate statistical quotation\nas to the fortunes of Mr. Rockefeller\nand Mr. Carnegie.\nTwo irreverent and irrelevant de\nscriptions of the personal habits of St.\nPeter.\nMention of President Roosevelt, the\nlate Mr. Havemeyer and Senator\nBeveridge, each in the worst possible\ntaste.\nOne vague plan to cure the evils of\na great and necessary industrial\neconomy by killing it.\nThe National Idea.\n(New York World.)\nWith our iron roads whirling people\nacross a dozen state lines in a day,\nwith the telegraph obliterating distance\nand time, with moral problems clam\noring tor solution because of the dis\ncord of state statutes, and with the\nstrong fist of capital clutcning at\nmonopolies from sea to sea, it is idle\nto object to nationalism. \u2018Every in\nstinct of repugnance to corrupt city\nadministration, every impulse of im\npatience with the feebleness of state\ngovernments and of disgust at their\nlack of agreement in the face of like\nperplexities and common foes, but\nstrengthens the tendency of the people\nto put their reliance upon the greater\nand wider powers of the general gov\nernment. Scan as one will the prece\ndents and traditions, argue as one nfay\nfor close or loose construction of the\nconstitution, nationalism is inevitable.\nThe national idea is the growth of\nstern necessity. More than ever be\nfore. because of newer and greater\nproblems, it is necessary for the re\npublic to turn for political guidance to\nits real leaders of intellect, to its\nstrong captains of independent\nthought.\nSOOTHES AND HEALS.\nHyomei Medicates the Air You\nBreathe and Gives Quick Relief in\nCatarrhal Troubles.\nBe wise in time and use Hyomei at\nthe first warning of catarrhal troubles.\nDo not let the disease extend along\nthe delicate mucunus membrane,\ngradually going from the nose to the\nthroat, thence into the bronchial\ntubes, and then downward until the\nlungs are reached and you are in dan\nger of consumption.\nHyomei will cure all curable forms\nand stages of catarrh. It is so uni\nformly successful In curing this com\nmon yet dangerous disease that Bow\nditch Webster take all the risk of a\ntrial treatment and agree absolutely\nto refund the money if anyone uses\nHyomei and does not get relief.\nThere is no other treatment for ca\ntarrh that is like Hyomei or just as\ngood. None can take its place, none\ngive such quick and sure relief and at\nso little cost. Its medication is\nbreathed through a pocket inhaler that\ncomes with every outfit, thus reaching\nthe most remote cells of the air pas\nsages, killing the catarrhal germs and\nsoothing and healing the irritated\nmucuous membrane.\nBegin the use of Hyomei today and\nyou will soon find that the offensive\nbreath, the droppings into the throat,\nthe discharge from the nose and all\nother symptoms of catarrh are over\ncome and cured. The complete outfit\ncosts but 11.00 and Bowditch 